<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-117-034 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 213 337</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  July 1991 v10 n7 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Look out, barium titanate! (researchers discover a newphotorefractive material) (Newsfronts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cunningham, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Researchers at IBM's Almaden Research Center discover a newphotorefractive material, a polymer based upon a mixture of epoxyand an organic substance used in photocopy and laser printtechnology.andP;  The new substance can be used in ways similar tobarium titanate, but it is less expensive to build.andP;  Thephotorefractive effect of barium titanate and strontium bariumniobate comes from an asymmetry formed during the crystal'sgrowth.andP;  In the new material, asymmetry occurs when the polymer isheated and softened, an external electric field is applied, and acooling process locks the materials into place.andP;  The materialsinvolved in the creation of this polymer include epoxy polymerBisA-NPDA, an organic photoconductor DEH, and epoxy formulationNNDN-NAN.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. Almaden Research Center(Research).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     New TechniquePhotochemistryOpticsCrystalsResearch and DevelopmentMaterials Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>